// LeetCode 1283: Find the Smallest Divisor Given a Threshold\n// Problem: Find smallest divisor such that sum of ceil(nums[i]/divisor) <= threshold\n// Approach: Binary Search on divisor value with early termination\n\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n\n    int smalldiv(vector<int> &temp, int divi)\n    {\n        long long total = 0;\n        for(int i = 0;i< temp.size();i++)\n        {\n            total += ceil((double)temp[i] / (double)divi);\n        }\n        return (int)total;\n    }\n    int smallestDivisor(vector<int>& nums, int threshold) {\n\n        int n = nums.size();\n\n        int maxi = -1;\n\n        for(int i =0; i<n; i++)\n        {\n             if(nums[i]> maxi)\n             {\n                maxi = nums[i];\n             }\n        }\n        \n        int low = 1;\n        int high = maxi;\n\n        int ans = 0;\n\n        while(low<=high)\n        {\n            int mid = (low + high)/2;\n\n            int total = smalldiv(nums,mid);\n\n            if(total<=threshold)\n            {\n                ans = mid;\n                high = mid -1;\n            }\n\n            else{\n                low = mid +1;\n                \n            }\n        }\n\n        return ans;\n    }\n};\n\n/*\nTime Complexity: O(n log m)\n- n: size of nums array (calculating sum in each binary search iteration)\n- m: maximum element in nums (binary search range from 1 to max)\n- Binary search: O(log m) iterations\n- Each iteration computes sum: O(n)\n- Total: O(n log m)\n\nSpace Complexity: O(1)\n- Only constant extra space used\n\nAlgorithm (Binary Search on Divisor):\n1. Find range: low=1, high=max(nums)\n   - Smallest divisor is at least 1\n   - Largest needed divisor is max element (would give ceiling of 1)\n2. Binary search on divisor values:\n   a. Calculate mid = (low + high) / 2\n   b. Compute sum of ceil(nums[i] / mid) for all elements\n   c. If sum <= threshold:\n      - This divisor works, try smaller (high = mid - 1)\n      - Update answer = mid\n   d. Else:\n      - Need larger divisor (low = mid + 1)\n3. Return smallest valid divisor\n\nKey Insight - Monotonic Property:\n- As divisor increases, sum decreases (monotonic)\n- If divisor d works, all divisors > d also work\n- If divisor d fails, all divisors < d also fail\n- This monotonicity enables binary search\n- Find minimum divisor where condition holds\n\nCeiling Division:\n- ceil(a / b) = (a + b - 1) / b using integers\n- Or use floating point: ceil((double)a / (double)b)\n- Code uses floating point approach\n\nExample 1:\nInput: nums = [1,2,5,9], threshold = 6\n\nRange: low=1, high=9\n\nIteration 1: mid=5\nsum = ceil(1/5) + ceil(2/5) + ceil(5/5) + ceil(9/5)\n    = 1 + 1 + 1 + 2 = 5\n5 <= 6? Yes, ans=5, high=4\n\nIteration 2: mid=2\nsum = ceil(1/2) + ceil(2/2) + ceil(5/2) + ceil(9/2)\n    = 1 + 1 + 3 + 5 = 10\n10 <= 6? No, low=3\n\nIteration 3: mid=3\nsum = ceil(1/3) + ceil(2/3) + ceil(5/3) + ceil(9/3)\n    = 1 + 1 + 2 + 3 = 7\n7 <= 6? No, low=4\n\nIteration 4: mid=4\nsum = ceil(1/4) + ceil(2/4) + ceil(5/4) + ceil(9/4)\n    = 1 + 1 + 2 + 3 = 7\n7 <= 6? No, low=5\n\nlow > high, return ans=5\n\nOutput: 5\nVerification: ceil(1/5)=1 + ceil(2/5)=1 + ceil(5/5)=1 + ceil(9/5)=2 = 5 <= 6 ✓\n\nExample 2:\nInput: nums = [2,3,4,5], threshold = 8\n\nInitial: low=1, high=5\n\nIteration 1: mid=3\nsum = ceil(2/3) + ceil(3/3) + ceil(4/3) + ceil(5/3)\n    = 1 + 1 + 2 + 2 = 6\n6 <= 8? Yes, ans=3, high=2\n\nIteration 2: mid=1\nsum = 2 + 3 + 4 + 5 = 14\n14 <= 8? No, low=2\n\nIteration 3: mid=2\nsum = ceil(2/2) + ceil(3/2) + ceil(4/2) + ceil(5/2)\n    = 1 + 2 + 2 + 3 = 8\n8 <= 8? Yes, ans=2, high=1\n\nlow > high, return ans=2\n\nOutput: 2\n\nEdge Cases:\n- threshold >= n (length of array): divisor=1 always works\n- Single element array: divisor is that element\n- All elements same: still binary search applies\n- Very large numbers: use long long in sum calculation\n\nMonotonic Behavior Visualization:\nnums = [1, 2, 5, 9]\n\nDivisor 1: 1 + 2 + 5 + 9 = 17\nDivisor 2: 1 + 1 + 3 + 5 = 10  (decreasing)\nDivisor 3: 1 + 1 + 2 + 3 = 7   (decreasing)\nDivisor 4: 1 + 1 + 2 + 3 = 7   (plateaus possible)\nDivisor 5: 1 + 1 + 1 + 2 = 5   (decreasing)\nDivisor 9: 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 = 4   (decreasing)\n\nMonotonically decreasing (or staying same)\nAllows binary search to find minimum divisor\n\nBinary Search Correctness:\n- Property: If divisor d satisfies condition, all d' > d satisfy it\n- Property: If divisor d fails condition, all d' < d fail it\n- These properties are exactly what binary search needs\n- Answer space is contiguous: {valid divisors form a range [ans, max]}\n\nWhy Not Linear Search:\n- Would be O(n * max_element) - too slow\n- Binary search is O(n * log max_element) - much better\n- Especially when max_element is large\n\nFloating Point Consideration:\n- ceil((double)a / (double)b) works\n- Has potential precision issues\n- Alternative: (a + b - 1) / b is more precise\n- But code uses floating point for clarity\n\nTime Complexity Breakdown:\n- Finding max: O(n)\n- Binary search iterations: O(log m)\n- Each iteration calculates sum: O(n)\n- Total: O(n + n log m) = O(n log m)\n\nComparison with Other Approaches:\n1. Linear search: O(n * max_element) - too slow\n2. Binary search (current): O(n log max_element) - optimal\n3. Dynamic programming: not applicable here\n\nThis binary search on answer technique is common pattern for:\n- Minimum resource to achieve goal problems\n- Verify feasibility function\n- Binary search on answer value\n*/